\begin_layout Section*
Products and services
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main products of DICE are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 series of games and their derivatives, which are similar with different
 branding and story content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the core of the big AAA-titles lies what is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

game engine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is the technical foundation (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

platform
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) of the game - we might say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the engine runs the game
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Designing and producing a game translates into creating input for the engine.
 The engine can thus be shared among different games of different genres.
 The game engine at DICE is called Frostbite, and has been in continual
 development since 2006
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
an earlier engine was called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Refractor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 at DICE by the Core Technology/Engineering team.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Frostbite comprises, apart from the core engine itself, a suite of tools
 and programs necessary to maintain efficient workflows for game designers.
 Frostbite in all versions is used by more than twenty different titles
 from EA.
 This makes DICE, and the Core Technology team, a service provider to other
 teams across EA.
 The life-cycle of a Frostbite version seems to last around three years,
 in step with the development cycle of games that adopt it.
 Hence, in order to develop a game with a competetive engine version and
 reduce complexities of heterogenous versions, game development and engine
 releases benefit by being synchronized.
\end_layout

