 Patrick Söderlund explains:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The minute you start designing and innovating with money in mind, you're
 ultimately not going to be successful.
 You need to put the money aside and say, "How do we actually make something
 that is fundamental, that helps our games, and essentially the people that
 play them, to have a better and more fun experience?"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
/.../ Without taking any credit, I started the Frostbite initiative 10 years
 ago [laughs] and it came out of frustration, having to build an engine
 every time in every game.
 "We're spending 50 per cent of our time making an engine.
 I want to spend 90 per cent of our time making a game," so we said, "Let's
 build something that can live over time, that is upgradable, that is where
 a lot of the focus goes against user interface, and tools and pipelines,
 then add to it as we go on," 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
/.../ That's kind of an open-source mentality that we use, and people want
 to contribute to the engine, so we may have 300 people, but in essence
 we have 3,000 people contributing to the code, and it's getting better
 and better and better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that the motivation behind Frostbite was primarily to factor the
 technical work out from the creative work, allowing designers and artists
 more freedom.
 Continuous investment into Frostbite, and contributions from teams across
 EA, has given EA and DICE critical competitive advantages and represents
 a huge barrier to entry for competitors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This represents a type of outside-in perspective in defining requirements
 and business strategy, where the staff acts as the main testing demographic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tools and processes (we might say operation resources and capabilities)
 are improved and added to over each iteration.
 As this practice grows within EA, the quality and quantity of the tools
 grow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Characteristics and processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are various models by which to characterize the processes in software
 development; for ease of discussion we might we consider the different
 levels of work of a game studio as;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
title/game Work on a title might span over years and requires large resources,
 careful planning, and many teams and disciplines.
 Specifications of a title start as loose, and become more defined as work
 progresses.
 The total capacity to produce titles is low, and each represents a risk.
 For predictability and practicality there is little variety within titles,
 for example: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield 4
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield4: China Rising
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield 4: Second Assault
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
project Projects are diverse items of work with clear goals and estimates
 of time requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
feature A feature is a small item of work that can be completed by one person
 or a small team.
 Progress of projects can be measured by features.
 Features can be diverse, specialised and teams/people must work on different
 types of features.
 The aim is to have high volume throughput of features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can see that the business implications of starting work on a title are
 large.
 Between 2011 and 2013, six subtitles of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield 3
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 were released.
 Between 2013 and 2015, eight sub-titles of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Battlefield 4
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 were released.
 We see that one strategy to lower risk and maximize return on technology
 investment and brand loyalty, is to reuse elements from the present generation
 in releases of sub-titles during the development phase of the next technology
 generation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Rigidity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the size of Frostbite and the titles, each title requires large
 teams working in cycles of one-two years, which creates the need for a
 predictable pipe-line of titles.
\end_layout

